{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502179","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502179"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:40:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:40:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1832"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1832","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1832"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.08,0.11,0.64,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1832"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47466"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1832","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1832"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1832"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32182"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"33"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"5826"},{"type":"tags","id":"6561"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5348"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6410"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12164"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47466","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/47466"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man is retrieved from the scene of a head-on motor vehicle crash in which he was the driver. Police state that they estimate the collision to have occurred at approximately 60-70 km/h. On review, he is able to provide details of the event, but appears to be short of breath and complains of pain in the chest. He denies any abdominal pain. On examination, his pulse rate is 118/min and blood pressure 103/67 mmHg. He is tender on the right side of his chest. The percussion note is resonant to all areas and the breath sounds are normal. A chest X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Left apical pulmonary contusion","Left pneumothorax","Pericardial effusion","Thoracic aortic rupture","Rupture of right hemidiaphragm"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe chest X-ray shows widening of the posterior mediastinum and this is most likely to be due to a rupture of the thoracic aorta. \u003Cstrong\u003EThoracic aortic rupture\u003C/strong\u003E (TAR) is a potential cause of death following blunt trauma. It may occur due to direct shearing from fractured vertebrae, increased aortic pressure at the time of impact, or - as in this case - from rapid deceleration at the time of impact. Rapid deceleration may cause the heart and ascending aorta to \u0027swing forward\u0027 while the descending aorta remains fixed to the posterior chest wall (retroperitoneal structure). There is transection at the junction of the mobile aortic arch and the fixed descending aorta. The radiological appearances of a widening of the mediastinum may reflect blood leaking from the aorta. Angiography is the gold-standard investigation of TAR.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeft apical pulmonary contusion\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered following blunt trauma. However, there is no sign of localised injury on the chest X-ray. Furthermore, a pulmonary contusion would not explain the widened mediastinum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis is unlikely to be a \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft pneumothorax\u003C/strong\u003E as lung fields are visible to the borders of the chest cavity. On examination, pneumothoraces are hyperresonant to percussion and breath sounds are absent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough \u003Cstrong\u003Epericardial effusion\u003C/strong\u003E would fit much of the clinical picture, it does not fit with the widened mediastinum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Erupture of the right hemidiaphragm\u003C/strong\u003E may occur during blunt trauma when abdominal pressure exceeds the strength of the diaphragm. This is not visible on the chest X-ray as there are no visible bowel loops in the chest. However, it is important to note that right-sided ruptures may be more difficult to identify due to the presence of the liver.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Thoracic aortic rupture may occur due to rapid deceleration forces during motor vehicle accidents"],"references":["O\u2019Conor CE. Diagnosing traumatic rupture of the thoracic aorta in the emergency department. Emergency Medicine Journal 2004;21:414-419. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1726377/","Simon LV, Lopez RA, Burns B. Diaphragm Rupture. In: StatPearls [Online]. 2022. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470214/","Weerakkody, Y., Knipe, H. Pulmonary contusion. In: Radiopaedia.org [online]. 2022. Available at: https://radiopaedia.org/articles/pulmonary-contusion"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32182"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1832"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15770"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15770","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15770"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/eb248e1e-859f-4f5b-a0e8-6929d99a4b06.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/eb248e1e-859f-4f5b-a0e8-6929d99a4b06.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":500,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32182","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/32182"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-23T21:12:06